Been having a good time breaking down film with my athletes, so figured I would share some of those breakdowns! Enjoy!
.
1. Here’s @aaloncruz’s latest fight against Bobby King. We knew King was a really good kickboxer, and the more time we spent kickboxing the tougher the fight would become. King sometimes will allow himself to be backed up to the “warning tracks” which is the 3-5 feet right before the cage wall. So we wanted to pressure him to that point and then level change to a double leg. In this first example Aalon does a great job of reading and reacting to a lead hook. He level changes into a double entry and locks his hands to secure the takedown out in open space. 
.
2. Tough fight going into the 3rd round. We had it 1-1 with the momentum in our favor. We knew that we wanted to get back to pressure and back to a wrestling entry. Aalon does a great job of getting into a clinch position to drive King back to the fence. Mocks a right hook to disguise the double entry, locks his hands and completes the double. He remains on top the rest of the round, to win the round, and ultimately the fight. 
.

Happy 4th! America af’ flowing with @aaloncruz! Excited to watch him defend home soil in a little over a month. Since working with Aalon he’s been on a nice little streak, and has leveled up in a lot of areas.Particularly just a better understanding of his own game. I don’t really credit myself, as much as I credit the importance in the coach/fighter relationship. Specifically what you can accomplish when two people are willing to sacrifice their time and bodies to work towards a common goal. While they both maintain honest and constant communication. Coaches can get on their soap boxes and talk about what fighters should be doing, but let’s make sure we lead by example so they have a frame of reference 🙏

I get a lot of questions about Vedic Thai. So I thought I would show you what a session looks like ❤️

Rooted from Thai and Vedic Indian cultures it heals the spiritual, emotional and physical bodies, revealing deep layers of the self which are often left untouched and unexplored. With deep compression massage along the sen lines (energy channels), fluid and static range of motion and assisted stretches, activation of marma points, breath enhancing compressions and so much more✨️

Fun fact: the Thai culture has been using Thai bodywork as an essential limb of their healthcare system for over 2500 years!
